Type: Text Length: 40

County
Enter the county where the mailing address is located.
Type: Text Length: 40

Tax Jurisdiction Code
A key that describes the tax jurisdiction. The jurisdiction code specifies the tax authorities to which sales tax is to be paid, and in what amount.
In some countries, such as Brazil, India, Canada, and the USA, sales tax is paid at local level aswell as national level. To reflect the multi-level local tax levels in addition to the national taxes in the tax calculation, the jurisdiction code is used in addition to the tax code. The tax jurisdiction code always describes the location to which the goods were delivered or where a service was provided.
Type: Text Length: 80

Employee ID*
A unique code assigned to an employee within the enterprise to provide verification of identity.
Enter the numeric or alphanumeric key from your legacy system to identify each employee.
Type: Text Length: 20(80) - see introduction

National Bank Code Type
A description or code that defines the national bank code for bank transactions.
If you use a national bank code to identify the bank, you must specify a national bank code type as well if available for a country.
Examples: ABA (US Federal Reserve Identification Code) ACH (Clearing House ID, US) FW (FedWire Routing ID, US) CH (CHIPS Universal ID, US) CP (CHIPS Participant ID, US) BL (German Bankleitzahl) NSC (Irish National Clearing Code)
Type: Text Length: 80

National Bank Code
If you use the National Bank Code Type to identify the bank, also define the National Bank Code, account number and account name.
Type: Text Length: 35

SWIFT/BIC
The Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication.
Within the context of international payment transactions, the SWIFT code (standard throughout the world) enables banks to be identified without the need to specify an address or bank number. SWIFT codes are used mainly for automatic payment transactions.
If you have an IBAN, you do not require a SWIFT/BIC code.
Note: SWIFT/BIC code does not include the account identification part of IBAN.
Type: Text Length: 11

IBAN
A code used to uniquely identify individual bank accounts that assists the correct processing of bank transfers, particularlyinternational transfers. IBAN is primarily used in Europe, and includes information that identifies the country and the bank where the account is held. In some countries, the bank branch where the account is held can also be identified from the IBAN.
Only relevant in some countries.
Type: Text Length: 34

Bank Account Number
A unique seriesof digits used to identify a bank account.
Type: Text Length: 35

Account Owner
The name of the person or company who owns a bank account.
Type: Text Length: 60

Account Type
Defines the kind of account used by the business partner.
Examples are checking account, debit card, and savings.
Only relevant in some countries.
Type: Text Length: 80
